binding.p: Early modern binding. Parchment over cardboard. 4 raised bands and endbands, endbands visible. 2 holes, back and front, for straps. , in brown ink: Magister sententiarum; in pencil: Lombardus; in ink: 26; stamped in gold: A 151; in ink on paper label: e. 30. 3. 13.; visible in ink on a the remnants of a paper label: XXVIII .

history.origin: 12th century, last half, or 13th century, first half. The layout and style of decoration in combination with the manuscript's early provenance would suggest France as the place of origin.
history.provenance: According to a note on , the manuscript was given to the community at Plessis-lèz-Tours by Iohannes Garelli, almoner of Louis XI. An identical note is found in Paris, Bibliothèque Nationale, Latin 6833, p. 161. It is not known how the manuscript came to the National Library. It is listed in Jache's catalogue of 1698 (U 122) as 192 and given the new number 26 ; it is listed as number 26 in the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e), and as e. 30. 3. 13 in Hammarsköld's catalogue of the 19th century (U 133). The signum partially visible on the paper label at the bottom of the spine has not been identified.
